        <fact xml:id="fact-AI4masscomputation">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider a solid where the cross section of the solid at <m>x=x_i</m> has area <m>A(x_i)</m>, and the density when <m>x=x_i</m> is <m>\delta(x_i)</m>.  Suppose the interval <m>[a,b]</m> represented the <m>x</m> values of this solid.  If one sliced the solid into <m>n</m> pieces of width <m>\Delta x=\frac{b-a}{n}</m>, then one can approximate the mass of the solid by <me>\sum_{i=1}^n \delta(x_i)A(x_i)\Delta x.</me>
                    <figure>
                <caption>Solid approximated with prisms of width <m>\Delta x</m>.</caption>
                    <image xml:id="Solidmassapproximation" width="100%">
                        <description>Solid approximated with prisms of width <m>\Delta x</m>.</description>
                        <latex-image>
                          \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw[thick,->] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node[anchor=north west] {\tiny$x$};
                            \draw plot [
                                samples=100,
                                domain=0:4,
                                ] (\x,{(\x)^(0.5) });
                            \draw plot [
                                samples=100,
                                domain=0:4,
                                ] (\x,{-1*(\x)^(0.5) });   
                            \draw (4,-2) -- (4,2);
                            

                            \foreach \i in {0,...,20}{
                                \draw (0.2*\i, {-1*sqrt(0.2*\i)})--(0.2*\i+0.2, {-1*sqrt(0.2*\i)})--(0.2*\i+0.2, {sqrt(0.2*\i)})--(0.2*\i, {sqrt(0.2*\i)})--(0.2*\i, {-1*sqrt(0.2*\i)});
                                \draw [fill=blue, opacity=0.2] (0.2*\i,{-1*sqrt(0.2*\i)}) rectangle (0.2*\i+0.2,{sqrt(0.2*\i)});
                            };
                            
                            \draw [decorate, decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt,mirror},yshift=-0.4pt](2,-1.414) -- (2.2,-1.414) node[black,midway,yshift=-0.5cm] {\footnotesize $\Delta x$};

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
            </figure>
                </p>
                <p>
                    We can then find actual mass by taking the limit as <m>n\to\infty</m>:  <me>\lim_{n\to\infty} \left(\sum_{i=1}^n \delta(x_i)A(x_i)\Delta x\right)=\int_a^b \delta(x)A(x) dx.</me>
                    <figure>
                <caption>Solid mass.</caption>
                    <image xml:id="Solidmass2" width="100%">
                        <description>Solid mass.</description>
                        <latex-image>
                          \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw[thick,->] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node[anchor=north west] {\tiny$x$};
                            \draw plot [
                                samples=100,
                                domain=0:4,
